<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does commercial ice machine repair cost in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Our commercial diagnostic fee is $120, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most commercial ice machine repairs run between $180 and $500. Water inlet valve, water pump, bin sensor, or harvest cycle component replacement is toward the lower end. Compressor or sealed system work runs higher. Descaling service alone runs $120–$200 depending on machine size. We provide a full written estimate before any work begins."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should a commercial ice machine be cleaned and descaled in Los Angeles?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every 6 months minimum — and every 3–4 months in high-volume operations or kitchens with particularly hard water. Los Angeles municipal water runs at 300–400 mg/L total dissolved solids — among the hardest in the US. Commercial ice machines running this water deposit mineral scale continuously inside the water distribution system, evaporator plates, and water inlet valve. Scale reduces ice production, changes ice quality, and eventually causes component failure. The 6-month schedule isn't manufacturer padding — in LA it's genuinely necessary."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "There's pink or black slime in my ice machine bin — is this a health issue?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes — immediately. Pink slime (Serratia marcescens) and black mold in an ice machine bin are bacterial and fungal contamination that make ice unsafe to serve. This is not an aesthetic issue. Serving ice from a contaminated machine is a health code violation — the Los Angeles Department of Public Health can issue violations and require temporary closure if discovered during an inspection. Stop using the machine for ice service immediately, call us, and we'll perform a full sanitization service. Do not just run ice through — the contamination is typically in the water tray, distribution tubes, and bin walls, not just surface-visible."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "My ice machine is producing less ice than normal — what causes that?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "In Los Angeles specifically, scale buildup is the most common cause — mineral deposits coating the evaporator plates reduce the surface area available for ice formation, directly reducing output. The machine cycles normally but makes thinner, smaller cubes that yield less ice per cycle. Other causes: low refrigerant, failing water pump reducing flow to distribution tubes, clogged water filter restricting inlet flow, or a dirty condenser coil causing the machine to run hot. We assess all four before recommending parts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I repair or replace my commercial ice machine?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Ice machines last 7–10 years with proper maintenance. If your machine is under 6 years old, repair almost always makes sense. If it's over 10 years old and needs a compressor or sealed system work, the math changes — we'll give you an honest assessment including the cost of a comparable replacement unit. Machines that have had repeated neglected maintenance are often better replaced because the corrosion and scale throughout the system make it difficult to restore full performance even after repair."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do you repair Hoshizaki, Scotsman, and Manitowoc ice machines?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Hoshizaki, Scotsman, Manitowoc, and Ice-O-Matic are the four brands we service most in LA's commercial market. We carry parts for Hoshizaki specifically and source parts for the others through same-day commercial distributors. All refrigerant work is performed by EPA 608 certified technicians."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does the 90-day warranty cover on ice machine repairs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Every commercial ice machine repair carries a 90-day warranty on parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. Descaling and cleaning services are covered by a 30-day satisfaction guarantee — if scale-related issues return within 30 days, we re-service at no charge."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

