      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01 — About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">Two reasons LA commercial ice machines fail more than in other cities: hard water and deferred cleaning.</h2>

        <p>Los Angeles water at 300–400 mg/L total dissolved solids is among the hardest municipal supply in the country. Every gallon that passes through a commercial ice machine leaves mineral scale behind — on the evaporator plates, in the water distribution tubes, inside the water inlet valve, and on the bin sensors. In a machine producing 300+ pounds of ice per day, this accumulation is fast. The result: reduced ice output, smaller cubes, cloudy ice, and eventually component failure.</p>

        <p>The second issue is deferred cleaning. Most health department guidelines require commercial ice machine cleaning every 6 months. In LA's hard water environment, the practical standard is closer to every 3–4 months for high-volume operations. When cleaning is skipped, scale combines with biofilm to create the pink or black slime that shows up in ice bins — and that's when a routine maintenance issue becomes a health code emergency.</p>

        <p>We offer both services: mechanical repair when something has failed, and cleaning/descaling when the machine needs sanitation and scale removal. Both are important, and we assess which your machine actually needs rather than defaulting to the more expensive option.</p>

        <div class="alert-red">
          <div class="al-label">🚨 Pink or Black Slime in the Ice Bin?</div>
          <p><strong>Stop serving ice immediately.</strong> Pink slime (Serratia marcescens) and black mold in an ice machine are bacterial and fungal contamination. Serving this ice is a health code violation — LADPH can issue citations and require closure. Call <strong>{phone}</strong> for emergency sanitization service. Do not simply run the machine — contamination is in the water tray, distribution tubes, and bin walls, not just the surface.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

