<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Making Ice At All</h3>
        <p>Water inlet valve failure (no water entering the machine), bin sensor reading full when it isn't, or a refrigerant issue preventing the evaporator from freezing. We check the water supply first — a closed water supply valve is the most common "broken machine" that isn't actually broken.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Slow Ice Production / Low Output</h3>
        <p>In LA specifically, mineral scale on the evaporator plates is the most common cause — scale coats the freezing surface and reduces ice formation per cycle. Also: low refrigerant charge, partially clogged water distribution tubes, or a dirty condenser causing the machine to run hot and slow.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Harvest Cycle Failure</h3>
        <p>Ice forms on the evaporator plates but doesn't release into the bin — the harvest cycle uses hot gas or warm water to loosen ice, and when the harvest valve or hot gas solenoid fails, ice accumulates until the machine locks out. Common on Hoshizaki and Scotsman modular units.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Dirty, Cloudy, or Off-Tasting Ice</h3>
        <p>In Los Angeles, mineral content in the water is the first suspect — high TDS produces cloudy ice regardless of machine condition. Scale and biofilm buildup in the water distribution system, water tray, and bin produce off-flavors and discoloration. A cleaning service resolves both; a water filter upgrade prevents recurrence.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Machine Overheating / Shutting Down</h3>
        <p>Condenser coils clogged with dust and kitchen grease cause the machine to overheat and shut down on its thermal protection. In LA's warm ambient conditions, condensers foul faster and heat rejection is harder. Monthly condenser brush cleaning by staff, plus semi-annual deep cleaning by a technician, prevents this failure mode.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Mold or Slime in the Ice Bin</h3>
        <p>Pink or black growth in the ice bin or water tray is bacterial/fungal contamination — not a cleaning aesthetic but a health and safety issue. Requires full machine disassembly, sanitization of all water-contact surfaces, and treatment of the bin. We document the service for your health department compliance records.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- MOLD ALERT -->
    <div class="mold-block">
      <div class="m-label">🚨 Health Code — Mold &amp; Slime in Ice Machines</div>
      <h3>Why ice machine contamination is a LADPH inspection failure — not just a maintenance issue</h3>
      <p>The Los Angeles Department of Public Health (LADPH) considers ice a food product. Bacterial or mold contamination in an ice machine is treated with the same seriousness as contamination in any food contact surface. An inspector finding pink slime or black mold in an ice bin during a routine inspection will issue a violation, require immediate corrective action, and may require temporary suspension of ice service.</p>
      <p>The contamination is almost always more extensive than the visible surface. Pink slime grows throughout the water flow path — distribution tubes, water tray, and the underside of the bin where it's not visible during normal operation. A surface wipe-down does not resolve it. We perform full machine disassembly, sanitize all water-contact surfaces with approved food-safe sanitizer, and provide a service record documenting the corrective action.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- LA HARD WATER -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — LA Hard Water &amp; Ice Machines</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Why Los Angeles ice machines need more maintenance than the manufacturer's manual says</h2>

    <div class="water-block">
      <div class="w-label">💧 Los Angeles Water Quality</div>
      <h3>300–400 mg/L TDS — every cycle deposits minerals, every day accelerates scale</h3>
      <p>Los Angeles municipal water runs at 300–400 mg/L total dissolved solids — predominantly calcium carbonate, magnesium, and silica. A commercial ice machine producing 300 lbs of ice per day is processing approximately 30–40 gallons of water through its system. Every gallon leaves mineral residue on contact surfaces. In a week, it's a thin film. In three months without descaling, it's a measurable layer affecting ice formation. In six months, it's thick enough to reduce output by 15–25% and change ice quality noticeably.</p>
      <p>Most manufacturer cleaning schedules assume "average" water hardness of 150–200 mg/L. LA water at 300–400 mg/L means scale accumulates 2–3x faster than their schedule accounts for. The practical implication: in LA, every 3–4 months for high-volume machines, every 6 months as an absolute minimum.</p>

      <div class="w-grid">
        <div class="w-item"><strong>LA water TDS</strong><span>300–400 mg/L — 2–3x harder than manufacturer baseline assumptions</span></div>
        <div class="w-item"><strong>Scale accumulation rate</strong><span>High-volume machine: visible scale in 6–8 weeks. Significant scale in 3 months.</span></div>
        <div class="w-item"><strong>Production impact</strong><span>Heavy scale reduces ice output 15–25% and changes cube clarity and size</span></div>
        <div class="w-item"><strong>Component damage</strong><span>Scale hardens inside water inlet valve and pump — eventually causes failure if not cleared</span></div>
        <div class="w-item"><strong>Recommended interval</strong><span>Every 3–4 months for high-volume; 6 months minimum for all LA commercial machines</span></div>
        <div class="w-item"><strong>Water filter upgrade</strong><span>Carbon + scale inhibitor filter reduces descaling frequency and improves ice clarity</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

